# Task 04: Asset Loader + Data Types

## Objective
Build the asset loading system and define all TypeScript interfaces for game data. Load all JSON content files with typed getters.

## Prerequisites
Task 01 must be complete. The project scaffold and content-samples/ folder must exist.

## Requirements

### Game Data Interfaces (src/shared/types.ts)
Add these interfaces (reference `docs/DATA-SCHEMAS.md` for full field details):

```typescript
export interface Race {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  statModifiers: { str: number; dex: number; con: number; int: number; wis: number; cha: number };
  allowedClasses: string[];
  multiclassOptions: string[][];
  levelCaps: Record<string, number>;
  traits: string[];
  baseSpeed: number;
  description: string;
}

export interface CharacterClass {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  hitDie: string;
  primaryStat: string;
  savingThrows: string[];
  armorProficiency: string[];
  weaponProficiency: string[];
  spellcasting: {
    enabled: boolean;
    type: 'arcane' | 'divine' | null;
    spellList: string;
    slotsPerLevel: number[][];
    preparationType: 'memorize' | 'know_all';
  };
  abilities: { level: number; ability: string; description: string }[];
  xpTable: number[];
  description: string;
}

export interface Monster {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  type: string;
  hitDice: string;
  ac: number;
  attackBonus: number;
  attacks: { name: string; damage: string; type: string; range?: number }[];
  speed: number;
  abilities: string[];
  xp: number;
  loot: { gold: string; table: string };
  sprite: string;
  encounterArt: string;
}

export interface Spell {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  class: string;
  level: number;
  type: string;
  targetType: string;
  areaRadius?: number;
  range: number;
  damage?: string;
  healing?: string;
  maxDamageDice?: number;
  saveType?: string;
  saveEffect?: string;
  duration?: number;
  description: string;
  effect?: string;
}

export interface Item {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  type: string;
  subtype?: string;
  value: number;
  weight: number;
  description: string;
  effect?: Record<string, any>;
}

export interface EquipmentItem extends Item {
  slot: string;
  damage?: string;
  attackBonus?: number;
  acBonus?: number;
  classRestrictions?: string[];
}

export interface DungeonMap {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  width: number;
  height: number;
  tileset: string;
  startPosition: { x: number; y: number; facing: string };
  tiles: number[][];
  events: MapEvent[];
  randomEncounters?: { table: string; frequency: number };
}

export interface MapEvent {
  x: number;
  y: number;
  trigger: string;
  type: string;
  data: Record<string, any>;
  id?: string;
}

export interface EncounterTable {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  entries: { monsters: { id: string; count: string | number }[]; weight: number }[];
}
```

Adjust these interfaces to match the actual structure of the JSON files in `content-samples/`. Read each JSON file to verify field names match.

### AssetLoader (src/renderer/src/engine/AssetLoader.ts)
- Singleton pattern
- `async loadAll(): Promise<void>` — loads all JSON files from content-samples/
- Typed getters:
  - `getRaces(): Race[]`
  - `getClasses(): CharacterClass[]`
  - `getMonsters(): Monster[]`
  - `getMonster(id: string): Monster | undefined`
  - `getSpells(): Spell[]`
  - `getSpellsByClass(className: string): Spell[]`
  - `getItems(): Item[]`
  - `getEquipment(): EquipmentItem[]`
  - `getEncounterTables(): EncounterTable[]`
  - `getEncounterTable(id: string): EncounterTable | undefined`
  - `getMap(id: string): DungeonMap | undefined`
- Handle loading errors gracefully (log warning, continue with empty array)
- For Electron: use fetch() to load from the app's content-samples directory

### Dice Utilities (src/shared/dice.ts)
```typescript
export function roll(notation: string): number
// Parses "2d6", "1d8+3", "3d4-1", "d20"
// Returns the total result

export function rollMultiple(notation: string, count: number): number[]
// Roll the same notation multiple times

export function rollAbilityScore(): number
// Roll 4d6, drop the lowest die, sum the remaining 3

export function parseNotation(notation: string): { count: number; sides: number; modifier: number }
// Parse "2d6+3" into { count: 2, sides: 6, modifier: 3 }

export function rollRange(notation: string): { min: number; max: number }
// Calculate the min and max possible values for a notation
```

### Tests
- `src/shared/__tests__/dice.test.ts`:
  - `roll('2d6')` returns value between 2 and 12
  - `roll('1d8+3')` returns value between 4 and 11
  - `roll('d20')` returns value between 1 and 20
  - `parseNotation('2d6+3')` returns `{ count: 2, sides: 6, modifier: 3 }`
  - `rollAbilityScore()` returns value between 3 and 18
  - `rollRange('2d6')` returns `{ min: 2, max: 12 }`
  - Run 1000 rolls of each to verify range bounds (statistical test)

- `src/shared/__tests__/types.test.ts`:
  - Verify that content-samples JSON files can be parsed as the defined interfaces
  - Load each JSON file and assert it has the expected top-level structure

## Done When
- All interfaces match the actual JSON data in content-samples/
- AssetLoader loads all JSON files and returns typed arrays via getters
- Dice roller correctly handles all notation formats (2d6, 1d8+3, d20, 3d4-1)
- `npm test` passes (dice tests + type validation tests)
- `npm run build` succeeds

# Task 09: Phase 1 Integration Test

## Objective
Verify the complete Phase 1 flow works end-to-end. Run the full loop, write automated integration tests, fix any bugs found, and document known issues.

## Prerequisites
Tasks 05, 06, 07, and 08 must ALL be complete.

## Requirements

### Manual Test Flow
Run the application (`npm run dev`) and execute this exact sequence:
1. App launches → Main Menu appears with 4 options
2. Press DOWN to highlight "Load Game" → Press ENTER → "No saved games" message appears
3. Press ESCAPE → back to Main Menu
4. Select "About" → SRD attribution text appears → Press ESCAPE → back to menu
5. Select "New Game" → Character Creation begins at Step 1
6. Create Character 1: Human Fighter, roll stats, Lawful Good, name "Roland"
7. Create Character 2: Elf Mage, roll stats, Neutral Good, name "Aelindra"
8. Create Character 3: Dwarf Cleric, roll stats, Lawful Good, name "Durgin"
9. Create Character 4: Halfling Thief, roll stats, Chaotic Good, name "Pip"
10. Decline to add more → Party Review screen
11. View each character's detail sheet — verify stats, equipment, HP, AC
12. Reorder: move Durgin to position 1 (tank first)
13. "Begin Adventure" → Town placeholder appears
14. Save game to Slot 1
15. Close app entirely
16. Relaunch app → Main Menu
17. "Load Game" → Slot 1 shows "Party of 4 — Lv 1"
18. Load Slot 1 → Verify all 4 characters intact with correct stats, equipment, names
19. Verify party order matches (Durgin first)

### Automated Integration Tests (src/__tests__/integration/)

#### `character-creation.test.ts`
```typescript
// Test the full character creation data flow
// - Create GameState
// - Add 4 characters with valid race/class/stat combinations
// - Verify each character has correct:
//   - HP (max hit die + CON modifier)
//   - AC (10 + DEX modifier + armor bonus)
//   - Starting equipment per class
//   - Racial stat modifiers applied correctly
// - Verify party size = 4
// - Remove one character → party size = 3
// - Reorder → verify order changed
```

#### `save-load.test.ts`
```typescript
// Test serialization roundtrip
// - Create GameState with 4 fully equipped characters
// - Set various world state flags (explored maps, defeated bosses)
// - Serialize to SaveGame JSON
// - Deserialize back to GameState
// - Assert EVERY field matches:
//   - All 4 characters with all stats
//   - Equipment on each character
//   - Gold amount
//   - Current location
//   - World state flags
//   - Play time
//   - Version string
```

#### `state-machine.test.ts`
```typescript
// Test state transitions
// - MAIN_MENU exists and is initial state
// - CHARACTER_CREATION exists
// - TOWN exists
// - Transitions between states call enter()/exit() correctly
// - No stale DOM elements after state exit
```

### Bug Fixes
- Fix any issues found during the manual or automated tests
- Common issues to check for:
  - DOM elements not cleaned up on state exit (memory leak)
  - Input events leaking between states
  - Stat calculations off-by-one
  - Equipment not affecting AC
  - Save/load losing data fields
  - Menu wrapping behavior
  - Canvas not resizing on window resize

### Known Issues Documentation
Create `docs/KNOWN-ISSUES.md`:
```markdown
# Known Issues

## Phase 1 (Foundation)

_List any bugs or limitations found during integration testing._

- (example) No music/audio yet — audio system comes in Phase 7
- (example) Town screen is placeholder — will be built in Phase 2
```

If no issues are found, create the file with a "No known issues" note.

### Code Cleanup
- Remove any debug console.log statements (except initialization messages)
- Ensure all TypeScript has proper types (no `any` where avoidable)
- Verify imports are clean (no unused imports)
- Ensure consistent code style across all files created in Phase 1

## Done When
- Complete manual test flow (steps 1-19) succeeds without errors
- All automated integration tests pass
- `npm test` passes (unit tests + integration tests)
- `npm run build` succeeds
- `docs/KNOWN-ISSUES.md` exists
- No TypeScript compilation warnings
- Application starts cleanly with no console errors

# Task 14: Tile Map Data Structures & Visibility

## Objective
Build the core data structures for dungeon maps — TileMap loader, tile types, and the FogOfWar visibility computation. No rendering yet; this is the model layer.

## Prerequisites
Task 09 must be complete. AssetLoader exists.

## Requirements

### Tile Types (src/shared/types.ts — add to existing)
```typescript
export enum TileType {
  Open       = 0,
  Wall       = 1,
  Door       = 2,
  LockedDoor = 3,
  SecretDoor = 4,
  StairsUp   = 5,
  StairsDown = 6,
  Water      = 7,
  Pit        = 8,
}

export interface MapEvent {
  id: string;
  x: number;
  y: number;
  type: 'encounter' | 'treasure' | 'trap' | 'trigger' | 'npc' | 'message';
  data: Record<string, unknown>;  // type-specific payload
  triggered?: boolean;             // once-only events
}

export interface GameMap {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  width: number;
  height: number;
  tiles: number[][];               // tiles[y][x] (row-major)
  events: MapEvent[];
  randomEncounters?: {
    table: string;                 // ref into encounter-tables.json
    chance: number;                // 0..1 per step
  };
  startPosition?: { x: number; y: number };
  stairsUpTo?: string;             // map id this connects up to
  stairsDownTo?: string;
}
```

### TileMap (src/renderer/src/dungeon/TileMap.ts)
```typescript
export class TileMap {
  readonly map: GameMap;

  constructor(map: GameMap) { this.map = map; }

  static fromJSON(json: unknown): TileMap;

  getTile(x: number, y: number): TileType;          // Wall if out of bounds
  isWalkable(x: number, y: number): boolean;        // Open/Door (unlocked)/Stairs/Water (Pit blocks)
  isOpaque(x: number, y: number): boolean;          // Walls + closed doors block vision
  getEventAt(x: number, y: number): MapEvent | undefined;
  markEventTriggered(eventId: string): void;
}
```

Notes:
- `isWalkable`: Open, Door, LockedDoor (blocks until unlocked, but flag separately via `isOpenDoor`), SecretDoor (blocks until found), StairsUp, StairsDown. Water = walkable but slow. Pit = blocks.
- `isOpaque`: Wall, SecretDoor (until found), LockedDoor + closed Door. Doors track open/closed state externally in DungeonState (Task 16).

### FogOfWar (src/renderer/src/dungeon/FogOfWar.ts)
Tracks per-tile visibility state. Three states:
- `Hidden` (never seen) — black
- `Visited` (seen before, not currently) — dimmed
- `Visible` (currently in line of sight) — fully lit

```typescript
export enum TileVisibility {
  Hidden = 0,
  Visited = 1,
  Visible = 2,
}

export class FogOfWar {
  readonly width: number;
  readonly height: number;
  private grid: Uint8Array;        // flattened y*width+x

  constructor(width: number, height: number);

  getVisibility(x: number, y: number): TileVisibility;
  isVisible(x: number, y: number): boolean;
  isVisited(x: number, y: number): boolean;
  setVisited(x: number, y: number): void;
  setVisible(x: number, y: number): void;

  // Compute visible tiles from a position using line-of-sight with VISIBILITY_RADIUS
  computeVisible(map: TileMap, originX: number, originY: number, radius: number): void;

  // Serialize for save game
  toJSON(): { width: number; height: number; data: number[] };
  static fromJSON(json: { width: number; height: number; data: number[] }): FogOfWar;
}
```

#### Visibility Algorithm
Use simple symmetric shadowcasting OR Bresenham line-of-sight for each tile within Chebyshev distance ≤ VISIBILITY_RADIUS (from constants.ts = 4):

For each candidate tile (x,y) where `max(|dx|,|dy|) <= radius`:
1. Walk a Bresenham line from origin to (x,y)
2. If any intermediate tile is opaque, stop — tiles beyond are Hidden
3. Otherwise mark the tile Visible and Visited

Before computing: downgrade all currently-Visible tiles to Visited (so they stay dim when out of LOS).

